ARTICLE 3-INTERCONNECTION CONDITIONS 3.1. Operating Responsibility; Avoidance of Unauthorized Use and Control of System Disturbances (a) Each Party shall have facilities or contractual arrangements adequate to serve its own load and shall exercise reasonable care to design, construct, maintain, and operate its facilities, in accordance with Good Utility Practice, and in such manner as to avoid the unauthorized utilization of the facilities of the other Party (hereinafter referred to as "Unauthorized Use"). Any Party may install and operate on its system such relays, disconnecting devices, and other equipment, as it may deem appropriate for the protection of its system or prevention of Unauthorized Use, consistent with Good Utility Practice. (b) The Parties shall maintain and operate their respective systems in a safe and reliable manner so as to minimize, in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards, the likelihood of a disturbance originating in either system that might cause impairment to the delivery of power and energy by the other Party or of any transmission or generation facilities interconnected with the system of the other Party. (c) For the avoidance of doubt, neither Party shall have responsibility for the other Party's failure to comply with any Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards, except to the extent such failure is caused directly or indirectly by such Party's 5 transmission facilities or conditions on such facilities or such Party's noncompliance with any Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards. (d) Notwithstanding the foregoing, (x) DOE shall be responsible for the operation of the Project Interconnection Facilities and the testing and maintenance thereof, and (y) OVEC shall be responsible for the operation of the OVEC Interconnection Facilities and the testing and maintenance thereof, each in accordance with the following: (i) Upon the request of the applicable balancing authority, reliability coordinator or pursuant to Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards, the Parties shall be capable of immediately operating each of the circuit breakers connected to the Project Interconnection Facilities or the OVEC Interconnection Facilities (as applicable); (ii) The Parties shall cooperate in the analysis of any electrical disturbances to their respective systems, including providing access to information relating to such disturbances, including information provided by or with respect to fault recorders, protective relays, breaker operation, and sequence of event recorders; and (iii) The Parties shall, upon request from the other Party, provide the other Party with all test data and other information in such Party's possession or control as necessary to confirm such Party's completion of testing, operating and maintenance activities necessary in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards (including the activities listed on Schedule 3.1, but excluding any such activities or the applicable intervals to the extent such activity is no longer necessary for compliance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards due to a change in such practice, laws, regulations or standards after the date of this Agreement). (e) "Good Utility Practice" for purposes of this Agreement means any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts that, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be acceptable practices and methods or acts generally accepted in the region. 3.2. Interruption of interconnection (a) The interconnections provided under this Agreement may be interrupted, curtailed, suspended, reduced or disconnected upon such notice as is reasonable under the circumstances (i) by operation of automatic equipment installed for power system protection, (ii) by the non-defaulting Party, after the expiration of the applicable Notice Period after the other Party's Default as specified in Section 3.2(b), (iii) after consultation with the other Party, upon not less than thirty (30) days prior written notice to the other Party or such other shorter notice as is reasonable under the circumstances where thirty (30) days prior notice is not reasonably 6 practicable, when a Party deems it desirable for installation, maintenance, inspection, testing, repair or replacement of equipment on the Party's transmission system, or (iv) at any time that in the sole judgment of the interrupting Party such action is necessary to preserve the integrity of, to prevent or limit any instability on, or to avoid or mitigate an Emergency on its system, including (A) if a condition exists that presents an imminent physical threat to persons or property and such action appears necessary to OVEC or the DOE to protect such persons or property on their respective systems; or (B) to overcome transmission system reliability problems caused by an Emergency; provided that, with respect to any unscheduled disconnection permitted under this Section 3.2(a), the disconnecting Party shall give the other Party written notice of such disconnection (including its cause and likely duration) as promptly as reasonably practicable thereafter. Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement or where otherwise impracticable due to an Emergency, the Parties will manage their respective systems and resources to cause at least two (2) independent 345 kV interconnections between the Project and OVEC's transmission system to be in service at all times. Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, any disconnection shall continue only for so long as is reasonably necessary under Good Utility Practice and Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards, and the Party initiating the disconnection or with the means to resolve the basis for the disconnection will use its commercially reasonable efforts to promptly restore the interconnection to service. Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, the Parties shall cooperate with each other to restore the Interconnection Facilities to their normal operating state as soon as practicable consistent with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards. The Parties shall coordinate with each other, using Good Utility Practice and in accordance with Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards, to schedule any scheduled disconnections during periods of least impact to the Parties and their operations. (b) A Party shall have the right to interrupt, curtail, suspend, reduce or disconnect its interconnection to the other Party under this Agreement upon sixty (60) days' written notice (the "Notice Period") to the other Party, without any liability or responsibility, in the event that the other Party fails to comply in any material respect with any material obligation or other agreement under this Agreement (each of which shall constitute a "Default" hereunder), and such Default is not cured within the Notice Period; provided that, if such Default is not reasonably capable of being cured within the Notice Period, then the Default shall be deemed cured if the defaulting Party commences and diligently pursues action to remedy the Default within the Notice Period and thereafter remedies such Default within a reasonable period of time after receipt of such notice. For the avoidance of doubt, any dispute between the Parties as to whether a Default is not reasonably capable of being cured within the Notice Period, and what is a reasonable period of time after receipt of notice for such a Default to be cured, may be resolved using the dispute resolution provisions of Article 12 at any time; provided that no such referral shall limit a Party's remedies under this Agreement upon the expiration of such Notice Period. (c) With respect to any interruption, curtailment, suspension, reduction or disconnection permitted under this Agreement, OVEC or the DOE (the "Notifying Party") shall notify and coordinate such action with the other Party as is reasonably practical under the circumstances; provided, however, that with respect to the installation, maintenance, inspection, testing, repair or replacement of equipment, the Parties shall coordinate the timing of such action in order to minimize any adverse economic or programmatic impact on the Parties as a result of such action, recognizing that the safe and reliable operation of both Parties' systems is of paramount importance when determining the timing of such action. Such notice may be given orally or by facsimile to the other Party in accordance with the procedure(s) developed by the Operating Committee. Any interruption, curtailment, suspension, reduction or disconnection permitted under this Agreement shall be implemented and completed as soon as possible, consistent with Good Utility Practice and 7 Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards. The Notifying Party shall keep the other Party informed as to the anticipated duration of each such action. The Notifying Party shall restore the full interconnection under the Agreement, including restoring any connection at the Interconnection Points, as soon as practicable in accordance with Good Utility Practice and Applicable Laws, Regulations and Reliability Standards to the extent the condition resulting in interruption, curtailment, suspension, reduction or disconnection permitted under this Agreement has abated sufficiently to permit such resumption. (d) A Party's right to interrupt, curtail, suspend, reduce or disconnect the interconnection under this Agreement does not represent such Party's exclusive remedy, and such action shall be in addition to all other remedies available to such Party at law or in equity. Neither this Agreement nor any rights under this Agreement may be assigned by either Party without the written consent of the other Party, provided, however, that consent will not be unreasonably withheld except that (i) DOE may without OVEC's consent assign this Agreement or any of its rights under this Agreement, provided that (A) the assignee is a successor to DOE for purposes of operating the Project, (B) the assignee is wholly owned by the United States of America, (C) the assignee is authorized by law to assume, and does assume (by written instrument that is in form satisfactory to OVEC), all of the obligations and responsibilities of DOE and the United States of America under this Agreement, and (D) the assignment does not have the effect of relieving the United States of America of any of its obligations or responsibilities under this Agreement, and (ii) either party may, without the consent of the other party, assign this Agreement or any of its rights under this Agreement to a successor to all or substantially all of either its transmission facilities or, in the case of OVEC, its total property and assets, and OVEC may pledge this Agreement to secure its indebtedness incurred or to be incurred for the purpose of constructing facilities, and this Agreement or rights under this Agreement may be assigned or transferred without the consent of DOE to one or more persons who will assume the obligations of OVEC hereunder in connection with the enforcement of any such pledge. (b) The parties agree that no person or entity listed on the Federal Excluded Parties List (http://www.epls.gov/), prohibited under 12 U.S.C.95a, or prohibited in accordance with lists complied in the Treasury Department's Office of Foreign Assets Control may be the assignee or successor of this agreement. (c) In the event that any assignment of this Agreement or rights under this Agreement will become effective as herein provided, the parties will thereafter be entitled to take such action before, or make such filings with, any regulatory authority having jurisdiction with respect to any term or condition of this Agreement as they deem appropriate and in the event of such action by either party, the terms and conditions under which service will be rendered will be the terms and conditions as so changed or as will result from such action by or before any such regulatory authority. ARTICLE 12- DISPUTE RESOLUTION Any dispute arising between DOE and OVEC regarding their rights or the performance of their obligations under this Agreement shall be resolved according to the following procedures. 12.1. Informal Settlement 12.1.1 Procedure The DOE and OVEC shall attempt in good faith to resolve any dispute arising out of or relating to this Agreement promptly by negotiations between a vice president of OVEC or his or her designated representative and an executive of similar authority of DOE. Any Party may give the other Party written notice of any dispute, and within 20 calendar days after delivery of such notice, the executives shall meet at a mutually acceptable time and place, for a total of no less than six meetings, and thereafter as often as they reasonably deem necessary but at least weekly, to exchange information and to attempt to resolve the dispute. If the matter has not been resolved within 42 16 calendar days of the first meeting, either DOE or OVEC may initiate a mediation of the controversy or may initiate formal dispute resolution under Section 12.2 herein (provided that, with respect to any Default as defined in Section 3.2, the applicable period for resolution of disputes under this Section 12.1.1, shall not be required to be in addition to any applicable notice period thereunder). 12.1.2 Confidentiality All negotiations, settlement conferences, compromise discussions and any mediation conducted pursuant to this provision are confidential and shall be treated as compromise and settlement negotiations, subject to the provision of the Administrative Dispute Resolution Act, 5. U.S.C.571 et seq. 12.1.3 Preliminary Injunction Notwithstanding the foregoing provisions, DOE or OVEC may seek a preliminary injunction or other provisional judicial remedy if in its judgment such action is necessary to avoid irreparable damage or to preserve the status quo. 12.2. Formal Dispute Resolution In the absence of a voluntary resolution reached in accordance with Section 12.1, either DOE or OVEC may seek to resolve a dispute by seeking judicial relief or regulatory relief at FERC. The DOE or OVEC, with the written consent of the other Party, in the alternative may submit the dispute to non-binding arbitration which shall be conducted using any procedures agreed to by DOE or OVEC. No litigation or arbitration shall be commenced until not less than 20 calendar days after notice of the intention to commence such proceedings has been provided to both DOE or OVEC (which notice may be provided at any time, including during negotiations in accordance with Section 12.1), provided, however, that the preceding requirement shall not preclude DOE or OVEC from initiating litigation or arbitration to secure any legal right which may otherwise be forfeited due to limitation or requirements imposed by rule or statute. ARTICLE 13- FEDERAL PROVISIONS 13.1. Contingent upon Appropriations Without limiting OVEC's remedies under this Agreement, OVEC hereby acknowledges that where activities provided for in this Agreement extend beyond the current fiscal year, continued expenditures by the United States are contingent upon Congress making the necessary appropriations required for the continued performance of the United States' obligations under this Agreement. 13.2. Covenant against Contingent Fees OVEC warrants that no person or selling agency has been employed or retained to solicit or secure this Agreement upon an agreement or understanding for a commission, percentage, brokerage, or contingent fees, excepting bona fide employees or bona fide established commercial or selling agencies maintained by OVEC for the purpose of securing business. For breach or violation of this warranty, the United States shall have the right to annul, as to DOE/PPPO, this Agreement without liability or, in its discretion, to deduct from this Agreement price of consideration the full amount of such commission, percentage, brokerage, or contingent fee. 17 13.3. Reg. 16501 (1572), which provides, among other things, that the Parties will not discriminate against any employee or applicant or employment because of race, color, religion, sex, or national) origin, is incorporated by reference in this Agreement, as applicable. 13.5. Use of Convict Labor OVEC agrees not to employ any person undergoing sentence of imprisonment in performing this Agreement except as provided by 18 U.S.C. 4082(c)(2) and Executive Order 11755, December 29, 1973. 13.6. Anti-Deficiency Act The obligations of DOE under this Agreement are subject to the provisions of the Anti-Deficiency Act, 31 U.S.C. Section 1341, as amended.
